<seg id=1> 25-Story Detroit Building Razed to Ground in 30 Seconds </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP, Detroit) Haderson Mansion, with a 107-year-long history, was turned into shambles in 30 seconds the day before yesterday. </seg>
<seg id=3> The height of the steel framed building was 25 stories, and it was the highest building site to be destroyed by plastic explosives. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Haderson Mansion was once the largest retail store in the world and a symbol of Detroit. </seg>
<seg id=5> The explosive sound of 1215 kg of plastics explosives turned it into a 360 million kg shamble. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> At the local time of 5:45 pm, Haderson Mansion underwent a series of interior explosions. The heavy dust grew into huge fog and enveloped all the bystanders. </seg>
<seg id=7> One citizen noted," I never thought I would be completely blackened by the dust." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> When the mansion collapsed, some bystanders cheered loudly, while others wiped away tears, as they would never see the familiar building again. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> At its peak in 50s, about 100 thousand people shopped at Haderson Mansion daily. </seg>
<seg id=10> At that time, famous film stars such as Clarke Gable, Gregory Peck, and others could often be seen there. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Alche, Mayor of Detroit, had expressed to the public that the authorities would like to give the opportunity to throw the switch to the public, in order to raise US$150 thousand in charity donations. </seg>
<seg id=12> But, as Haderson Mansion stood for the past glory of Detroit, nobody wanted to set off the explosion themself. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> A man ,who advocated to protecting the building, uttered,"This is sad." </seg>
</p>
